.TH "hwatch" "1" "" "Version 0.4.2" "A modern alternative to the watch command, records the differences in execution results and can check this differences at after."
.hy
.SH NAME
.PP
\f[B]hwatch\f[R] - A modern alternative to the watch command, records
the differences in execution results and can check this differences at
after.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
\f[B]hwatch\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] \f[I]command\f[R]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
\f[B]hwatch\f[R] is like \f[I]watch\f[R] command, repeatedly executes a
\f[I]command\f[R] and displays its output.
However, the output results can be scrolled and displayed.
In addition, the difference of the execution result is recorded with the
time stamp, and it can be checked later.
When checking, it is also possible to display the diff with the previous
difference together.
.PP
If you specify it with options, the execution result can be recorded as
a log with json.
.SS Flags
.TP
-h, --help
Prints help information
.TP
-V, --version
Prints version information
.TP
-b, --batch
Output execution results to stdout.
NOTE: Operations with TUI are not possible in batch mode.
.TP
-B, --beep
beep if command has a change result.
.TP
-g, --chgexit [\f[I]count\f[R]]
Exit when output changes.
If no value is specified, exit after the first detected change.
If \f[V]count\f[R] is specified, exit after that many detected changes.
.TP
--border
Surround each pane with a border frame
.TP
--with-scrollbar
When the border option is enabled, display scrollbar on the right side
of watch pane.
.TP
--mouse
enable mouse wheel support.
With this option, copying text with your terminal may be harder.
Try holding the Shift key.
.TP
-c, --color
Interpret ANSI colors and style sequences and display in color.
It can be changed later by key binding.
.TP
-r, --reverse
Display text upside down.
.TP
-C, --compress
Compress data in memory.
Note: If the output of the command is small, you may not get the desired
effect.
.TP
-t, --no-title
Hide the UI on start.
Use \f[V]t\f[R] to toggle it.
.TP
--enable-summary-char
collect character-level diff count in summary.
.TP
-N, --line-number
Show line number.
.TP
-w, --wrap
Disable line wrap mode.
.TP
--no-help-banner
Hide the \[lq]Display help with h key\[rq] message
.TP
--completion \f[I]shell\f[R]
Output shell completion script.
Supported shells: bash, fish, zsh.
.PP
--no-summary
.PP
: disable the calculation for summary that is running behind the scenes,
and disable the summary function in the first place.
.TP
-x, --exec
Run the command directly, not through the shell.
Much like the \f[V]-x\f[R] option of the watch command.
.TP
-p, --use-pty
Run the command through a pseudo-TTY so commands that colorize on
terminals can keep color output.
.TP
-O, --diff-output-only
Display only the lines with differences during \f[V]line\f[R] diff and
\f[V]word\f[R] diff.
.TP
--ignore-spaceblock
Ignore diffs where only consecutive whitespace blocks differ.
.TP
--precise
Attempt to run as close to the interval as possible, regardless of how
long the command takes to run.
.SS Options
.TP
-A, --aftercommand \f[I]command to execute after difference occurs\f[R]
Executes the specified command if the output changes.
Information about changes is stored in json format in environment
variable \f[V]${HWATCH_DATA}\f[R].
.TP
--after-command-result-write-file
Pass \f[V]${HWATCH_DATA}\f[R] to \f[V]aftercommand\f[R] as a temporary
file path instead of inline JSON data.
.TP
-l, --logfile \f[I]logfile\f[R]
Output the command execution result and its time as a log in json.
The execution results that are recorded are only those that differ from
the previous execution results.
If a log file is already used, its contents will be read and executed.
.TP
-s, --shell \f[I]shell command\f[R]
shell to use at runtime.
can also insert the command to the location specified by {COMMAND}.
.TP
-n, --interval \f[I]seconds\f[R]
Seconds to wait between updates.
Default is \f[V]2\f[R].
.TP
-L, --limit \f[I]limit num\f[R]
Set the number of history records to keep.
only work in watch mode.
Set \f[V]0\f[R] for unlimited recording.
(default: 5000) [default: 5000]
.TP
--tab-size \f[I]num\f[R]
Specifying tab display size.
default 4 char.
.TP
--diff-plugin \f[I]path\f[R]
Load a diffmode plugin dynamic library.
Plugin-provided mode names can also be selected with
\f[V]-d/--differences\f[R].
.TP
-d, --differences \f[I][none, watch, line, word]\f[R]
set diff mode.
highlight changes between updates.
If only \f[V]-d\f[R] is specified, it will be a watch diff.
.RS
.PP
\f[I]none\f[R] \&...
Do not show diff (default).
.PP
\f[I]watch\f[R] \&...
Diff like watch command.
Specifying the \f[I]-d\f[R] option applies this mode.
.PP
\f[I]line\f[R] \&...
Can be done diff in line units.
.PP
\f[I]word\f[R] \&...
Can be done diff in line word units.
.RE
.TP
-o, --output \f[I][output, stdout, stderr]\f[R]
set output mode.
If you specify the output mode, the history pane will also display only
the history where the specified output mode has changed.
.TP
-K, --keymap \f[I]keymap\f[R]
Customize Keymap.\[u3000]Keymap is specified in the format of
\f[I]key=action\f[R] or \f[I]modifierkey-key=action\f[R]
.SS Configuration
.PP
If you always want to use some command-line options, you can set them in
the \f[V]HWATCH\f[R] environment variable.
For example, if you use \f[V]bash\f[R], you can add the following to
your \f[V].bashrc\f[R]:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
export HWATCH=\[dq]--no-title --color --no-help-banner\[dq]
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
\f[V]HWATCH_WATCH_FG\f[R] and \f[V]HWATCH_WATCH_BG\f[R] can also be used
to customize watch diff highlight colors.
Supported formats are named colors, \f[V]0-255\f[R], \f[V]#RRGGBB\f[R],
and \f[V]R,G,B\f[R].
.SH KEYBINDS
.PP
\f[B]hwatch\f[R] uses \f[I]Keybind\f[R] for operations on the command
execution screen.
It is the default keymap.
.TP
h
Show help message.
Press the \f[I]h\f[R] key again to return to the previous screen.
.TP
q
Exit hwatch.
.TP
c
Interprets ANSI colors and style sequences and displays them in color.
This is the same as the \f[I]-c(\[en]color)\f[R] option.
Press the \f[I]c\f[R] key again to return to the original.
.TP
n
Outputs the line number at the beginning of the line.
.TP
r
Displays the output of the watch pane in reverse order.
.TP
d
Highlight changes between updates.
This is the same as the \f[I]-d(\[en]differences)\f[R] option.
You can switch the diff mode by pressing the \f[I]d\f[R] key.
The \f[I]d\f[R] key toggles these in order.
Use the \f[I]0\f[R], \f[I]1\f[R], \f[I]2\f[R], and \f[I]3\f[R] keys to
switch directly to each mode.
.RS
.PP
\f[I]none\f[R] \&...
Do not show diff (default).
.PP
\f[I]watch\f[R] \&...
Diff like watch command.
Specifying the \f[I]-d\f[R] option applies this mode.
.PP
\f[I]line\f[R] \&...
Can be done diff in line units.
.PP
\f[I]word\f[R] \&...
Can be done diff in line word units.
.RE
.TP
o
Switch output mode at stdout, stderr, and output.
If you specify the output mode, the history pane will also display only
the history where the specified output mode has changed.
.TP
O
Display only the lines with differences during \f[V]line\f[R] diff and
\f[V]word\f[R] diff.
.TP
w
Toggle line wrap mode.
.TP
t
Switch display of header and history pane.
.TP
Backspace
Switch display of history pane.
.TP
m
Switch Mouse wheel support mode.
With this option, copying text with your terminal may be harder.
Try holding the Shift key.
.TP
0
Switch diff mode to \f[I]none\f[R].
.TP
1
Switch diff mode to \f[I]watch\f[R].
.TP
2
Switch diff mode to \f[I]line\f[R].
.TP
3
Switch diff mode to \f[I]word\f[R].
.TP
F1
Display only \f[I]Stdout\f[R].
.TP
F2
Display only \f[I]Stderr\f[R].
.TP
F3
Display \f[I]Stdout\f[R] and \f[I]Stderr\f[R].
.TP
Ctrl+P
Focus before keyword.
.TP
Ctrl+N
Focus next keyword.
.TP
Shift+O
Show only lines with differences(line/word diff mode only).
.TP
Shift+S
Show summary infomation in history.
.TP
+
Increase interval by 0.5 seconds.
.TP
-
Decrease interval by 0.5 seconds (As long as it\[cq]s positive).
.TP
p
Pause or resume command execution.
.TP
Tab
Switch the target(\f[I]history\f[R] or \f[I]watch\f[R] pad).
The target is operated with the \f[I]up\f[R] and \f[I]down\f[R] keys.
.TP
/
Filter diffs by keyword.
.TP
*
Filter diffs by regex.
